###############################################################################
# How to generate a GOOGLE_API_KEY (Google Cloud Console)
###############################################################################
# 1) Open Google Cloud Console: https://console.cloud.google.com/
# 2) Create or select a project (top-left project selector).
# 3) From the left menu, go to "APIs & Services" → "Library" and search
#    for "Custom Search API" (also called "Programmable Search Engine API").
# 4) Click "Enable" to enable the API for your project.
# 5) Go to "APIs & Services" → "Credentials" → "Create Credentials" →
#    "API key". A new API key will be generated (format typically starts
#    with "AIza...").
# 6) (Important) Restrict the API key: click the created key, then set
#    Application restrictions (HTTP referrers / IPs) and API restrictions
#    to only allow the "Custom Search API" to reduce risk if the key leaks.
# 7) Copy the generated key and put it into your local `.env` as
#    `GOOGLE_API_KEY`.

###############################################################################
# How to create a Custom Search Engine ID (`cx`) — Programmable Search Engine
###############################################################################
# 1) Open Programmable Search Engine: https://programmablesearchengine.google.com/
# 2) Click "Add" (or "New search engine") and follow the wizard. To search
#    the entire web, set the "Sites to search" field to something broad or use
#    the advanced options (note: some account options vary by region).
# 3) After creating the engine, open its Control Panel and copy the
#    "Search engine ID" (this is the `cx` value used by the API).
# 4) Paste that value into your `.env` as `GOOGLE_CX`.

###############################################################################
# Usage notes
###############################################################################
# - Add these two lines to your local `.env` (do NOT commit the file):
#
#   GOOGLE_API_KEY=AIzaSy...        # your real API key (keep secret)
#   GOOGLE_CX=0123456789:abcdefg    # your Custom Search Engine ID (cx)
#
# - In CI (GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, etc.) store these values as repository
#   secrets and inject them into the environment at runtime. Do not hardcode
#   secrets in the workflow files.
# - If a key is ever exposed, rotate (regenerate) it immediately and update
#   any deployments or CI secrets that use it.

# Example placeholders (safe; replace locally):
GOOGLE_API_KEY=your-google-api-key-here
GOOGLE_CX=your-google-cx-here

